{"questionId":"20767","questionHtml":"<p>Interpret your answer to part (e)(i) geometrically.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>(as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>→</mo><mo>∞</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></math>)</p>\n<p>the polygon becomes a circle of radius&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>R1</strong></em> for alternative responses such as:<br>the polygon becomes a circle of area&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></math> OR<br>the polygon becomes a circle of perimeter <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></math>&nbsp;OR<br>the polygon becomes a circle with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></math>.<br>Award <em><strong>R0</strong></em> for polygon becomes a circle.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"20767","referenceCode":"21M.3.AHL.TZ1.2e.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Interpret your answer to part (e)(i) geometrically.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"e.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.13—Limits and L’Hopitals"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}